# 1. what is the purpose of system calls?
To talk with the kernel as user-mode such that it can contact hardware 

Asking the operating system to do anything

# 2 What system calls have to be executed by a command interpreter or shell in order to start a new process on a UNIX system?
Fork() or exec() or wait() to wait for a process to finish, clone() what is shared and what is not

# 4. What is the main advantage of the layered approach to system design? What are the disadvantages of the layered approach?
-   Advantages 
    
    -   Dependancies are split up 
    - Testing is easier, since we can test each layer one by one  
    -   Can change one layer as long as it meets the specification 
-   Disadvantages 
    -   Slow since the calls has to be passed through n-layers
# 5. List five services provided by an operating system, and explain how each creates convenience for users. In which cases would it be impossible for user-level programs to provide these services? Explain your answer.
1.  User interface (to be able to interract with the system) 
    
2.  I/O operations (to be able to use the network card, mouse, headset – should be able to get input from e.g. keyboard, so some can be implemented in user-space) 
    
3.  File system (can be implemented in user-space, but not the root file system) 
    
4.  Ressource allocation 
    
5.  Program execution (allocate CPU , memory)

# 6.  How could a system be designed to allow a choice of operating systems from which to boot? What would the bootstrap program need to do?
It could store all the options with key:value pairs with name and the piece of memory to go to to find the boot-loader for this boot. So the bootstrap should just iterate over all the key:value pairs, and go to the value for the key chosen 

Bootstrap program is on the motherboard, such that we cannot delete it – if we delete the bootstrap program then we cannot retrieve any bootloaders

# 7.  What are the advantages and disadvantages of using the same system-call interface for manipulating both files and devices?

Advantages: 

-   Less system calls 
    
    -   Gives better portability 
        
-   Less interference 
    
    -   If files and devices both needs to access the disc, then it would be better if they are coherrent 
        

Disadvantages 

-   Difficult to interract with device i.e interract with it as it were a file

# 9.  How are iOS and Android similar? How are they different?
-   Interfaces (doesnt look the same) 
    
-   Designed with different approaches (iOS is more secure, cannot access as much compared to android, where you can see the root-file system.)

# 10.  What are the two models of interprocess communication? What are the strengths and weaknesses of the two approaches?
-   Shared memory 
    
    -   Faster 
        
    -   But has to synchronize such that they dont write to the same memory 
        
-   Mail box (message passing) 
    
    -   Slower (also has to copy each message into pointer for the placeholder) 
        
    -   No synchronize

# 11.  What is the main advantage of the microkernel approach to system design? How do user programs and system services interact in a micro-kernel architecture? What are the disadvantages of using the microkernel approach?

Microkernel: absolute bare minimum 

-   Has the ability for 
    
    -   Process schedualing 
        
    -   Memory 
        
    -   Interproccess communication 
        

Advantages: 

-   Easier to test 
    
-   More reliable 
    
-   Having things in userspace makes sure they have to communicate with eachother 
    
-   Faster to implement the kernel 
Disadvantages: 

-   Slower (more communication with the kernel, as you have to go through the kernel when interracting with another proccess)
